If the Moon's orbital plane were exactly the same as the ecliptic plane, lunar eclipses would be much rarer (C) and occur much less frequently. 

Lunar eclipses occur when the Earth, Sun, and Moon are almost in a line, with the Moon in the new moon phase. The Moon's slightly inclined orbit causes it to pass above or below the Sun's apparent position from our vantage on Earth, which results in the Earth's shadow falling on the Moon. When the Moon's orbital plane coincides with the ecliptic, it will not be in a new moon phase when the Earth, Sun, and Moon are aligned, leading to less frequent lunar eclipses.
